{"timestamp": "2025-12-16 15:27:49.346845", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: **Anomaly detected**\\n\\nAll of the routers are running BGP and have a full set of 10.0.x.x and 10.1.x.x routes in their tables, but two of the leaf switches are **sharing the same BGP router‑ID (172.16.0.35)** and, by extension, the same IP address on the spine‑leaf interconnect.  \\nIn a fabric where every router must have a unique router‑ID (and a unique IP on the inter‑leaf link), this duplication can cause:\\n\\n* **Route advertisement confusion** – the two leaves will appear as a single router to the spines, so the spines will only see one set of routes for the leaf’s AS.\\n* **ARP/LLDP conflicts** – the two leaf switches will send ARP/LLDP frames with the same MAC/IP, leading to packet loss or mis‑forwarding on the leaf‑spine links.\\n* **Potential routing loops or flapping** – if one leaf goes down, the spines may still advertise routes via the “duplicate” leaf, causing the other leaf to receive stale or incorrect next‑hop information.\\n\\n**Root cause**\\n\\nThe leaf routers were provisioned with identical BGP router‑IDs (172.16.0.35) and the same IP address on the spine‑leaf link. This violates the BGP requirement that each router in a given AS have a unique router‑ID and also violates the Layer‑2 requirement that each leaf‑spine interface have a unique MAC/IP.\\n\\n**Suggested fix**\\n\\n1. **Assign unique BGP router‑IDs**  \\n   * `leaf_router_0_0` → 172.16.0.35 (keep)  \\n   * `leaf_router_0_1` → **172.16.0.36** (or any unused ID)\\n\\n2. **Update the leaf‑spine interface IPs**  \\n   * `leaf_router_0_0` → 172.16.0.34 (keep)  \\n   * `leaf_router_0_1` → **172.16.0.36** (or any unused IP)\\n\\n3. **Re‑advertise the routes**  \\n   * After changing the router‑ID and interface IP, run `clear ip bgp *` (or `clear ip bgp * soft` if you want a graceful restart) on each leaf to force a fresh BGP session with the spines.\\n\\n4. **Verify connectivity**  \\n   * Ping from a host on `10.0.0.0/24` to a host on `10.1.0.0/24` and confirm that the path goes through the correct leaf and spine.  \\n   * Run `show ip bgp` again on all routers – the leaf routers should now advertise routes with their own IP as the next‑hop for the 10.1.x.x networks, and the spines should see distinct paths from each leaf.\\n\\nOnce the router‑IDs and IPs are unique, the fabric will behave as expected and the duplicate‑ID anomaly will be resolved., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='8dec6d06-0b19-45d3-a397-b8df0361971f'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "not_implemented", "id": ["langchain_ollama", "chat_models", "ChatOllama"], "repr": "ChatOllama(model='gpt-oss:20b', validate_model_on_init=True, temperature=0.0, base_url='http://10.68.186.140:11434')", "name": "ChatOllama"}}
